This is a GitHub Actions workflow designed to automate the execution of Proof of Concept (POC) scripts for a TOCTOU (Time-Of-Check to Time-Of-Use) race condition vulnerability, specifically targeting a simulated macOS environment for the Threema application.

Here is a breakdown of what this pipeline is doing:

Workflow Triggers
The workflow runs automatically when code is pushed to or a pull request is opened against the master or main branches. It also includes workflow_dispatch, which allows you to trigger the run manually from the GitHub Actions UI.

Job 1: run-bash-poc
Environment: Runs on the latest macOS runner (macos-latest).

Target Setup: It uses sudo to create a fake directory at /Applications/Threema.app and changes the ownership to the current runner user. This likely satisfies hardcoded file paths that the POC script expects to interact with.

Execution: It grants execution permissions to poc-race-simple.sh and runs it. This implies a shell-script-based attempt to trigger the race condition.

Job 2: run-rust-poc
Environment: Also runs on macos-latest.

Target Setup: Recreates the same dummy /Applications/Threema.app directory.

Compilation: Uses the dtolnay/rust-toolchain action to install stable Rust, then manually compiles the poc-toctou-full.rs file into an executable binary using the 2021 edition of Rust.

Execution: Runs the compiled Rust binary twice:

Once in its normal mode.

Once with an --aggressive flag, which likely spawns more threads or attempts the race condition in a tighter loop to increase the chances of winning the race.

Are you looking to debug a specific failure in one of these CI jobs, or would you like to discuss how to mitigate the underlying TOCTOU mechanics?

does it use official threema app?

No, it does not use the official Threema application.

Instead, it uses a fake or "dummy" setup. If you look closely at the Setup Dummy Threema App step in both the Bash and Rust jobs, it runs these exact commands:

Bash
sudo mkdir -p /Applications/Threema.app
sudo chown -R $USER /Applications/Threema.app
This simply creates an empty directory with the name /Applications/Threema.app and assigns ownership to the current user.

Why do it this way?
When testing a Time-Of-Check to Time-Of-Use (TOCTOU) vulnerability in an automated environment (like GitHub Actions), you rarely need the actual, fully-functioning application.

TOCTOU flaws are typically file system race conditions—meaning the vulnerability lies in how a script or system checks a file path and then subsequently interacts with it. By creating this fake directory, the environment provides the exact hardcoded file path the Proof of Concept script expects to target, allowing the race condition to be tested without the heavy overhead of installing a real macOS graphical application.

