How the Bash POC Tried to Work (and Why it Failed)
The log gives us a very clear picture of the exploit's intended mechanics:

The Setup: It creates a temporary directory and places the valid, officially signed Threema.app inside it.

The Payload: It creates a malicious LaunchDaemon plist file (490 bytes). The goal of this exploit is likely to trick the system into installing or executing this plist file with elevated privileges.

The Race: The script starts a loop attempting to rapidly swap the valid Threema.app directory with the malicious plist file.

The Critical Window: It simulates a call to SecStaticCodeCheckValidityWithErrors(). This is a macOS API used to check the digital signature of an application. The vulnerability theorizes that there is a time gap between when macOS checks the signature (Time-of-Check) and when it actually moves or uses the file (Time-of-Use).

The Failure: The log outputs: RESULT: payload.app is a DIRECTORY (app bundle) - Race FAILED, signature check held.

This means that after the simulated signature check completed, the file system still contained the original Threema.app directory, not the malicious plist file. The swap was unsuccessful.

Why Bash is a Tough Tool for TOCTOU
While the Rust script failed (likely due to Apple Silicon architecture timings or the bug being patched), a Bash script is at an even bigger disadvantage.

Bash is inherently slow for precision racing. Every file operation in Bash (like mv, cp, or ln) requires spawning a brand-new process. In the microsecond-level window of a TOCTOU vulnerability, the overhead of process creation in Bash makes it nearly impossible to win the race reliably against the macOS kernel, especially on extremely fast storage like the NVMe drives in Apple Silicon Macs.

Since both the aggressive Rust version and the Bash version failed entirely on Threema v1.2.50, it strongly suggests this specific race condition vector is either patched in this version or structurally incompatible with the ARM64 runner environment.